---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { BREW_INSTALL, MAC_DMG_URL, APP_VERSION } from '../consts.js';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<Base title="Installation Guide — Orcha" description="Install Orcha — download the Mac desktop app or set up the CLI from source.">
  <!-- INTRO -->
  <section class="install-intro">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h1>Installation Guide</h1>
      <p class="section-sub">
        Orcha has two parts that work together. <strong>Start with the command-line tool (CLI)</strong> —
        it’s the engine that powers orchestration inside Claude Code and Codex. Then, if you’d like a
        desktop dashboard, add the Mac app on top. The Mac app is not standalone: it needs the CLI
        installed first.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PREREQUISITES — HOMEBREW & DOCKER -->
  <section id="prereqs">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2 class="section-title">Before you begin — Homebrew &amp; Docker</h2>
      <p class="section-sub">
        Orcha installs through <strong>Homebrew</strong> (the Mac app store for command-line tools)
        and runs each project inside <strong>Docker</strong> (which keeps every project’s database
        and portal neatly isolated). If you already have both, skip ahead to Step 1. Otherwise set
        them up first — it’s a one-time thing and takes a few minutes each.
      </p>

      <h3 class="prereq-h">1. Install Homebrew</h3>
      <p class="section-sub">
        Open the <strong>Terminal</strong> app (find it with Spotlight — press ⌘&nbsp;Space and type
        “Terminal”), then paste this line and press Return:
      </p>
      <code class="code"><span class="c"># installs Homebrew, the Mac package manager</span>
/bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/HEAD/install.sh)"</code>
      <p class="note">
        When it finishes, it may print a couple of “Next steps” lines asking you to run two more
        commands so your Mac can find <code class="inline">brew</code>. Copy-paste those too — then
        you’re done.
      </p>

      <h3 class="prereq-h">2. Install Docker Desktop</h3>
      <p class="section-sub">
        With Homebrew in place, install Docker Desktop with one command:
      </p>
      <code class="code"><span class="c"># installs Docker Desktop</span>
brew install --cask docker</code>
      <p class="note">
        After it installs, open <strong>Docker Desktop</strong> once from your Applications folder
        and leave it running in the background — Orcha needs Docker switched on while you work.
        Prefer a regular installer? You can also download Docker Desktop from
        <a href="https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/">docker.com</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CLI (STEP 1 — REQUIRED) -->
  <section id="cli">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2 class="section-title">Step 1 — Install the CLI <span class="badge-req">Required</span></h2>
      <p class="section-sub">
        The <code class="inline">orcha</code> command-line tool spins up each project’s private
        Postgres + portal and brings the slash commands into your AI coding agent. Everyone needs
        this — including Mac app users. You’ll need Homebrew and Docker from the step above, plus
        Python 3.10+ and an AI coding agent (Claude Code or Codex).
      </p>
      <code class="code"><span class="c"># install the CLI with Homebrew</span>
{BREW_INSTALL}

<span class="c"># initialise orchestration inside any project</span>
orcha init --objective "Ship the thing" --as YourName</code>
      <p class="note">
        <strong>Updating:</strong> already have Orcha? Run
        <code class="inline">brew upgrade orcha</code> to get the latest CLI.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- MAC DESKTOP APP (STEP 2 — OPTIONAL) -->
  <section id="mac">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2 class="section-title">Step 2 — Add the Mac app <span class="badge-opt">Optional</span></h2>
      <p class="note note-prereq">
        <strong>Install the CLI first.</strong> The Mac app is not a standalone program — it’s a
        desktop dashboard for the CLI you installed above. Without the CLI (and Docker) running,
        the app has nothing to connect to.
      </p>
      <p class="section-sub">
        The Orcha desktop app bundles the portal dashboard in a native window — containers,
        agents, tasks and a live audit trail, all in one place. Universal build for both Apple
        Silicon and Intel Macs.
      </p>
      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href={MAC_DMG_URL}>Download Orcha {APP_VERSION} (.dmg)</a>
      </div>
      <p class="note">
        <strong>Signed &amp; notarized by Apple.</strong> Open the .dmg, drag Orcha into your
        Applications folder and launch it — it opens straight away with no security warnings.
      </p>
      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href={base}>Back home</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
